1736	WOLFPACK BATTALION	Mission: The Wolf Pack Battalion forges strong leaders and future Army officers through rigorous training and education, instilling values and discipline for military and civilian roles.\r\n\r\nVision: The Wolf Pack Battalion cultivates character-driven leaders capable of effective leadership in various contexts while nurturing responsible citizens dedicated to serving the United States.\r\n\r\nPurpose:\r\n\r\nLeadership: Developing confident, ethical leaders.\r\nAcademics: Promoting well-rounded academic excellence.\r\nCharacter: Instilling integrity and discipline.\r\nFitness: Ensuring physical readiness for leadership.\r\nCommunity: Fostering civic-minded leaders.\r\nMilitary Readiness: Preparing for commissioned officer roles.\r\nAdaptability: Equipping for dynamic environments.\r\n \r\n\r\nHistory: The University of Nevada (UNR) ROTC Wolf Pack Battalion traces its origins back to 1888 when it became part of the University Corps of Cadets. The ROTC officially began with the passage of the National Defense Act on June 3, 1916. It provided the opportunity for commissions in the Army as Second Lieutenants through a Four Year Program. The formation of the University Corps of Cadets was mandated by the Morrill Act of 1862 and the Nevada Constitution of 1864, which required the availability of military science and tactics courses at the university. Classes commenced on the Reno campus in 1896, coinciding with the opening of Morrill Hall. As the 20th century approached and during World War I, there was an anticipation that all eligible men under 27 would enroll as Cadets for their entire four undergraduate years. However, from 1888 to 1916, only the top three candidates received recommendations for commissioning. It wasn't until after World War I that students who completed the mandatory four years of training became eligible for commissions. After the war, general enrollment at UNR surged to 500 students and expanded to 1,000 students by 1936.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nWorld War II marked the most extensive military mobilization in U.S. history. In 1943, as part of this nationwide effort, the Army and the Army Air Force established a training presence at the University of Nevada, Reno, to educate officers and aircrews. Lincoln Hall was the primary administrative center during this period, which continued until the war's conclusion in 1945. Following World War II and throughout the 1960s, the Wolf Pack Battalion saw a decline in ROTC participation. Nevertheless, enacting the ROTC Vitalization Act of 1964 revitalized enrollment by introducing an innovative option—the two-year program. This program enabled students to complete a condensed six-week summer introductory course, positioning them to begin the ROTC advanced program in their junior year. This transformation injected fresh vitality into the Wolf Pack Battalion.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nPresent Day: Today, the Battalion's lasting legacy persists in shaping the leaders of tomorrow. The Wolf Pack Battalion proudly hosts a thriving community of Cadets and cadre. Our alums actively participate in missions and contingency operations across the globe, with dedicated service in regions such as Afghanistan, Iraq, and Kuwait. Astonishingly, nearly a century since its inception, the national ROTC program produces 65 percent of U.S. Army Officers.	2026-04-28 02:29:42.16815-07	Active	{civic,athletic,leadership}
